      "text": "1\n© 2025 Potomac Economics\nIMM Quarterly Report:\nWinter 2024\nPresented to:\nMarkets Committee of the Board of Directors\nCarrie Milton\nPotomac Economics\nMarch 11, 2025\n2\n© 2025 Potomac Economics\nWinter Summary\n• The MISO markets performed competitively, and market power mitigation was \ninfrequent during the winter.\n• Energy prices rose 31 percent compared over last winter as average gas prices \nrose 21 (Chicago) to 41 (Henry Hub) percent partly due to cold weather events.\n- Higher STR requirements to address uncertainty during Winter Storm Enzo led to \nefficient increases in STR and energy prices during the storm.\n- Peak load rose 1 percent year over year, while average load was up 6 percent.\n- MISO South hit a new all-time winter peak record during Winter Storm Enzo.\n- Ancillary service prices increased more than 90 percent over last winter.\n• MISO declared Conservative Operations for Winter Storms Blair, Cora and Enzo \nbut did not need to advance into its emergency procedures.\n- Unseas",
      "highlights": [
        "© 2025 Potomac Economics\nWinter Summary • The MISO markets performed competitively, and market power mitigation was \ninfrequent during the winter. • Energy prices rose 31 percent compared over last winter as average gas prices rose 21 (Chicago) to 41 (Henry Hub) percent partly due to cold weather events. - Higher STR requirements to address uncertainty during Winter Storm Enzo led to efficient increases in STR and energy prices during the storm. - Peak load rose 1 percent year over year, while average load was up 6 percent. - MISO South hit a new all-time winter peak record during Winter Storm Enzo. ... • MISO declared Conservative Operations for Winter Storms Blair, Cora and Enzo ... - Unseasonably cold conditions in January did not have any major market impacts. • Day-ahead congestion revenue fell 14 percent, while real-time congestion \nincreased by 6 percent. • Average hourly wind output was 14 percent higher than last year, and wind curtailments increased 19 percent, averaging 479 MW per hour.\n3\n© 2025 Potomac Economics\nQuarterly Summary\nValue\nPrior Qtr.\nPrior \nYear Value\nPrior \nQtr.\nPrior \nYear\nRT Energy Prices ($/MWh) $41.08 51% 31% FTR Funding (%) 98% 100% 96% Fuel Prices ($/MMBtu) Wind Output (MW/hr) 13,469 16% 14% Natural Gas - Chicago $3.75 95% 21% Wind Curtailed (MW/hr) 479 -39% 19% Natural Gas - Henry Hub $3.91 83% 41% Guarantee Payments ($M)4\nWestern Coal $0.81 1% 2% Real-Time RSG $7.4 89% -10% Eastern Coal $1.82 5% 1% Day-Ahead RSG $12.7 85% 16%\nLoad (GW)2 Day-Ahead Margin Assurance $10.5 -18% -3% ... Real-Time Congestion Value $541.4 38% 6% Cleared Quantity (MW/hr) 23,087 1% 3% Day-Ahead Congestion Revenue $320.9 -2% -14% % Price Insensitive 52% 49% 48% ... Ancillary Service Prices ($/MWh) Profitability ($/MW) $0.8 $0.4 $0.3 ... Spinning Reserves $2.54 -6% 40% Output Gap- Low Thresh. (MW/hr) 81 33 63\nSupplemental Reserves $0.99 32% 489% Short-Term Reserves $0.75 290% 831%\nKey: Expected Notes:\nMonitor/Discuss\nConcern\nWinter 5. Values include allocation of RSG.\n3. Net real-time congestion collection, unadjusted for M2M settlements. 4. Includes effects of market power mitigation. \nChange 1Change 1 1. Values not in italics are the values for the past period rather than the change. ... • In preparation for the storm, MISO was forecasting high uncertainty and increased ... • MISO managed the storm reliably without declaring an emergency or incurring \nsignificant costs. - Uplift totaled just $2.6 million, a reduction of more than 90 percent from Winter ... - Congestion during Enzo was $100 million, much lower than in prior storms. ... • We previously discussed concerns with out-of-market actions taken to manage ... - We recommended MISO rely more heavily on the markets to manage difficult ... • In 2024, we worked with MISO to develop Congestion Management Guidelines ... Quarterly Highlights: Winter 2025\n• MISO has significantly reduced inefficient commitments and associated RSG costs. • However, we are concerned that operators often do not commit resources that are ... aggregate pricing nodes to vary under specific conditions. This can: ... - Generate market shortfalls or uplift costs; \n• A modeling inconsistency at one location in one month this quarter: ... • To address these concerns, we continue to recommend that MISO implement ... Virtual Trading around Predictable Modeling Issues (Slide 45)\n8\n© 2025 Potomac Economics Submittals to External Entities and Other Issues\n• During the Winter Quarter, we: - Responded to several FERC questions related to prior referrals and FERC ... - Presented the IMM Fall Quarterly report to the MSC and ERSC, and the IMM’s ... • During the Winter Quarter, FERC issued an Order to Show Cause totaling nearly $1 billion for an energy efficiency provider that we referred for manipulation.\n9\n© 2025 Potomac Economics Quarterly Market Results:\nWinter 2025\n10 © 2025 Potomac Economics\nDay-Ahead Average Monthly Hub Prices\nWinter 2023–2025 ... Impact of 